<exploration xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="PA-circular-sine">

	<statement>
		<p>
			If we consider the unit circle in <xref ref="F-circular-sine-all-16">Figure</xref>, start at <m>t = 0</m>, and traverse the circle counterclockwise, we may view the height, <m>h</m>, of the traversing point as a function of the angle, <m>t</m>, in radians.  From there, we can plot the resulting <m>(t,h)</m> ordered pairs and connect them to generate the circular function pictured in <xref ref="F-circular-sine-first-graph">Figure</xref>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="F-circular-sine-first-graph">
			<caption>Plot of the circular function that tracks the height of a point traversing the unit circle.</caption>
			<image source="images/sine-labeling-graph" />
		</figure>

